---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "How School Catchment Areas Work in England",
  "description": "A complete guide to understanding school catchment areas in England — how they are set, how distance is measured, and how to find out if you are in catchment.",
  "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "catchment.school" },
  "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "catchment.school", "url": "https://catchment.school" },
  "mainEntityOfPage": "https://catchment.school/guides/how-school-catchment-areas-work"
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a school catchment area?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A school catchment area is the geographic zone within which a school gives admissions priority to applicants. Children living inside the catchment are more likely to receive a place, though this is not guaranteed for oversubscribed schools." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How is catchment area distance measured?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Most English schools use straight-line (crow-flies) distance from the child's home address to the school. Some use road-walking distance. The measurement method is specified in the school's admissions policy." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can a school change its catchment area?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. Catchment area boundaries are not fixed. They change each year based on the number and location of applicants. The 'last distance offered' in any given year reflects how competitive the school was, not a permanent boundary." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does living in a catchment area guarantee a school place?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "No. Living within a school's catchment area increases your priority but does not guarantee a place. If a school is oversubscribed, children with higher priority criteria (e.g. siblings, looked-after children) will be offered places first." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I find my school catchment area?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Search for your home postcode on catchment.school to find nearby schools, then visit your local authority's admissions page for the official catchment map and last-distance-offered data." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Base
  title="How School Catchment Areas Work in England — Complete Guide"
  description="Everything parents need to know about school catchment areas in England: how they are set, how distance is measured, oversubscription criteria, and how to check if you are in catchment."
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <nav class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6 flex gap-2">
    <a href="/" class="hover:underline">Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href="/guides" class="hover:underline">Guides</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>How catchment areas work</span>
  </nav>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-10">
    <article class="lg:col-span-2 prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <h1>How School Catchment Areas Work in England</h1>
      <p class="lead text-lg text-gray-600">
        Understanding catchment areas is one of the most important parts of the primary and secondary school
        admissions process in England. This guide explains what catchment areas are, how they are determined,
        and how to find out whether your home address falls within one.
      </p>

      <h2>What is a school catchment area?</h2>
      <p>
        A <strong>school catchment area</strong> is the geographic zone around a school within which
        applicants receive priority consideration when places are allocated. It is not a fixed legal boundary
        — it is a consequence of how many children apply and where they live.
      </p>
      <p>
        The term comes from the fact that in any given admissions round, the school "catches" children from
        a certain radius. That radius shrinks in competitive years when more families apply, and grows in
        quieter years.
      </p>

      <h2>How are school places allocated in England?</h2>
      <p>
        Schools in England use an <strong>oversubscription criteria</strong> system. When more children apply
        than there are places, the school works through a ranked list of criteria until all places are filled.
        The standard priority order is:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Looked-after children</strong> — children in local authority care, and previously looked-after children</li>
        <li><strong>Medical or social need</strong> — where attendance at that specific school is essential</li>
        <li><strong>Siblings</strong> — children with a brother or sister already attending the school</li>
        <li><strong>Distance</strong> — distance from home to school, nearest to furthest</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Some schools have additional criteria (such as faith attendance or feeder school links), which must
        be specified in their admissions policy.
      </p>

      <h2>How is catchment area distance measured?</h2>
      <p>
        The majority of English schools measure distance as a <strong>straight-line (crow-flies) distance</strong>
        from the child's home address to the school's main entrance or a designated point on the school site.
      </p>
      <p>
        A minority use <strong>road-walking distance</strong> — the shortest safe walking route. The method
        used must be published in the school's admissions policy. When in doubt, check the policy directly.
      </p>

      <h2>What is "last distance offered"?</h2>
      <p>
        After each admissions round, local authorities publish the <strong>last distance offered</strong>
        for each school — the distance at which the final place was allocated. This is the most useful data
        point for parents trying to assess their chances.
      </p>
      <p>
        If the last distance offered was 0.6 miles and you live 0.4 miles from the school, you were likely
        to receive a place — assuming no higher-priority criteria blocked you. But this figure changes
        year to year, so treat it as a guide, not a guarantee.
      </p>

      <h2>Do catchment areas change every year?</h2>
      <p>
        Yes. Catchment areas are not fixed — they shift each year based on demand. A school that previously
        offered places to children 1.2 miles away may only reach 0.8 miles in a year when applications surge.
      </p>
      <p>
        New housing developments, demographic changes, and school expansions all affect catchment distances.
        Never assume last year's boundary applies this year.
      </p>

      <h2>Does living in catchment guarantee a place?</h2>
      <p>
        No. Living within what you believe to be the catchment area does not guarantee a place.
        Higher-priority applicants (looked-after children, siblings) are always placed first, regardless
        of distance. In a high-demand year, siblings alone may fill all available places.
      </p>

      <h2>How to find your school's catchment area</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Search by postcode</strong> on catchment.school to see schools near your home address</li>
        <li>Visit the school's profile page and click "Find [council] catchment area documents"</li>
        <li>Download the school's <strong>admissions policy</strong> from the council or school website</li>
        <li>Check the <strong>last-distance-offered</strong> data published after the most recent admissions round</li>
        <li>Contact the school or local authority admissions team directly for the most current information</li>
      </ol>

      <!-- FAQ Section -->
      <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

      <h3>Can I appeal if I don't get a school place?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. All parents have the right to appeal a school place decision to an independent appeals panel.
        You can appeal even if you were outside the catchment area, as long as you applied in the first place.
        Appeals panels consider whether the admissions process was followed correctly and whether refusing
        a place causes more prejudice than admitting would.
      </p>

      <h3>What happens on the waiting list?</h3>
      <p>
        If your child does not receive a place, you can request to be placed on the school's waiting list.
        Waiting lists operate using the same oversubscription criteria — not on a first-come, first-served
        basis. Your position may improve or worsen as other families join or leave the list.
      </p>

      <h3>Are independent schools subject to catchment areas?</h3>
      <p>
        No. Independent (fee-paying) schools set their own admissions criteria and are not required to use
        catchment areas. State-funded schools — including academies and free schools — must follow the
        School Admissions Code, which governs how catchment and oversubscription criteria are applied.
      </p>
    </article>

    <!-- Sidebar -->
    <aside class="space-y-5">
      <div class="bg-indigo-50 rounded-xl p-5">
        <h3 class="font-semibold mb-3">Find schools near you</h3>
